[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] Drop as many secrets as you like in one file.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] Make sure to separate them via `---` for YAML and as extra, single objects in JSON.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] No, the private keys are only stored in the Secret managed by the controller (unless you have some other backup of your k8s objects).
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] There are no backdoors - without that private key used to encrypt a given SealedSecrets, you can't decrypt it.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] If you can't get to the Secrets with the encryption keys, and you also can't get to the decrypted versions of your Secrets live in the cluster, then you will need to regenerate new passwords for everything, seal them again with a new sealing key, etc.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] While treating sealed-secrets as long term storage system for secrets is not the recommended use case, some people do have a legitimate requirement for being able to recover secrets when the k8s cluster is down and restoring a backup into a new `SealedSecret` controller deployment is not practical.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] If you have backed up one or more of your private keys (see previous question), you can use the `kubeseal --recovery-unseal --recovery-private-key file1.key,file2.key,...` command to decrypt a sealed secrets file.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] You can check the flags available using `kubeseal --help`.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] A kubernetes `Secret` resource contains multiple items, basically a flat map of key/value pairs.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] SealedSecrets operate at that level, and does not care what you put in the values.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] In other words it cannot make sense of any structured configuration file you might have put in a secret and thus cannot help you update individual fields in it.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] Since this is a common problem, especially when dealing with legacy applications, we do offer an example of a possible workaround.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] Yes, you can provide the controller with your own certificates, and it will consume them.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] If you installed the controller in a different namespace than the default `kube-system`, you need to provide this namespace to the `kubeseal` commandline tool.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] Our images are being signed using cosign.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] The signatures have been saved in our GitHub Container Registry.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] If you want to use one controller for more than one namespace, but not all namespaces, you can provide additional namespaces using the command line flag `--additional-namespaces=<namespace1>,<namespace2>,<...>`.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] Make sure you provide appropriate roles and rolebindings in the target namespaces, so the controller can manage the secrets in there.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] The answer is yes, you can configure the number of retries in your controller using the flag `--max-unseal-retries`.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] This flag allows you to configure the number of maximum retries to unseal your Sealed Secrets.
[src:sealed-secrets/sealed-secrets] By default, the controller watches for `SealedSecret` resources across **all namespaces** using the `--all-namespaces` flag (which defaults to `true`).
